problem:
A line with slope equal to $1$ and a line with slope equal to $2$ intersect at the point $P(1,6),$ as shown. [asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);
draw((0,-1)--(0,10),EndArrow);
draw((-10,0)--(5,0),EndArrow);
draw((-6,-1)--(5,10),linewidth(0.8));
draw((-2.5,-1)--(3,10),linewidth(0.8));
label("$x$",(5,0),E);
label("$y$",(0,10),N);
label("$P(1,6)$",(1,6),SE);
label("$Q$",(-5,0),NW);
label("$R$",(-2,0),SE);
[/asy]What is the area of $\triangle PQR?$

chatgpt_solution:
First we find the equations of lines $QR$ and $PQ.$  The slope of line $PQ$ is 1 and it passes through $(1,6),$ so its equation is of the form
\[y = x + b\]for some number $b.$  Substituting, we find $6 = 1 + b,$ so $b = 5.$  Therefore, $PQ: y = x + 5.$

The slope of line $QR$ is 2 and it passes through $(1,6),$ so its equation is of the form
\[y = 2x + c\]for some number $c.$  Substituting, we find $6 = 2 + c,$ so $c = 4.$  Therefore, $QR: y = 2x + 4.$

We want to find the area of $\triangle PQR = \frac{1}{2} (1)(2) = \boxed{1}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);
draw((0,-1)--(0,10),EndArrow);
draw((-10,0)--(5,0),EndArrow);
draw((-6,-1)--(5,10),linewidth(0.8));
draw((-2.5,-1)--(3,10),linewidth(0.8));
label("$x$",(5,0),E);
label("$y$",(0,10),N);
label("$P(1,6)$",(1,6),SE);
label("$Q$",(-5,0),NW);
label("$R$",(-2,0),SE);
draw((1,0)--(1,5),dashed);
draw((0,6)--(5,6),dashed);
label("1",(1/2,6/2),SW);
label("2",(1.5,2.5),SW);
draw((1,5)--(5,6)--(-10/3,10/3)--cycle);
dot("R", (-10/3,10/3), W);
dot("Q",(-5,0), NW);
dot("P",(1,6),SE);
[/asy]
